<div id="Idea_4191"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/4191-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_4191">Speeding up immigration visa applications&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/10048-4049">trygsletteland</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">19 hours ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">I was born in the USA 62 years ago.  More than 4 years ago, I married a citizen of Brazil.  Incredibly, it took me 2 years to get her a Green Card.  A major contributor to the lengthy delay was the system the US Department of State ("State") uses to deliver its mail abroad.  Between Washington and Rio de Janeiro, State's mail takes anywhere from 6 to 8 weeks to be delivered.  If State used a combination of email and fax to deliver its mail, many months could have been trimmed off my and my wife's application for the immigration visa to which she was entitled within a reasonable period of time.</div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_4191" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_4191', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2294&topicID=4191')">Comments (0)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_4191"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2294">Legal & Policy Challenges</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_4191"></div>
